On Sunday, Macedonian citizens voted in a referendum if they want the country's name changed to "Northern Macedonia," a change that would settle a decade-old dispute with Greece that opposed its accession to the European Union and NATO.
Greece, which comprises a province called Macedonia, claims that the name of the neighboring country represents a claim on its territory and has opposed its accession to the EU and NATO.
The two governments agreed in June on the proposed new name, but opposition nationalists say the change would undermine the ethnic identity of Macedonia's majority Slav population.
President Gjorge Ivanov said he would not vote in the referendum and that a boycott campaign had raised doubts about the vote, and that the minimum 50% threshold needed to validate the referendum might not be reached.
The question on the ballot in the referendum will be: “Do you agree to join the EU and NATO by accepting the agreement with Greece?”
Proponents of the name change, including Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, say it is a price to be paid by Macedonia, one of the countries that resulted from the breakup of Yugoslavia, in order to be accepted into entities such as the EU and NATO.
“I am here today to vote for the future of the country, for young people in Macedonia to live free under the umbrella of the European Union, because that means safer lives for all of us,” Olivera Georgijevska, 79, told Skopje.
Although not legally obligatory, quite a few members of parliament said they would respect the outcome of the vote to make it decisive.
In order for the name to be changed, a two-thirds quorum is required in parliament.
The state’s electoral commission said no irregularities were reported until 1:00 p.m.
However, the turnout was only 16%, compared to 34% in the last parliamentary elections of 2016 when 66% of the people with the right to vote came to the vote.
“I came to vote for my children and for our place in Europe,” said Gjose Tanevski, 62, a voter from Skopje, the country’s capital.
On September 30, 2018, Macedonian Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, his wife Zorica, and their son Dushko voted for the referendum on changing Macedonia’s name, which will allow them to join NATO and enter the European Union.
In front of the parliament in Skopje, Vladimir Kavardarkov, 54, prepared a small scene and pulled chairs in front of the tents raised by those who would boycott the referendum.
“We support NATO and the EU, but we want to join them with our heads up, not the back door,” Kavadarkov said.
“We are a poor country, but we have dignity.
If we are not wanted by the name of Macedonia, we can go to other countries, such as China and Russia, and we can become part of the Eurasian Union.”
Prime Minister Zaev said NATO membership would bring much-needed investment to Macedonia, which has an unemployment rate of more than 20 percent.
“I think the majority will be in favor of changing the name, because more than 80% of our citizens are in favor of joining NATO and the EU,” Zaev said after casting his vote.
He said a result in favor of changing the name would be “confirming our future.”
According to a poll published Monday by the Policy Research Institute, between 30% and 43% of citizens with the right to vote will participate in the referendum, below the required number of participants.
According to another poll conducted by Telma TV in Macedonia, 57% of respondents plan to vote on Sunday.
Seventy percent said they would vote for change.
In order for the referendum to be valid, the vote must be 50% plus one vote.
The failure of the referendum would be the first serious blow to pro-Western government policy since taking over the government in May last year.
