“The sea is ours”: Bolivia hopes the court will reopen the way to the Pacific
Sailors patrol a naval headquarters full of cranes in La Paz.
Public buildings fly the blue flag, like the ocean.
The naval bases from Lake Titicaca to the Amazon are covered with the motto: “The sea is ours by right.
We have to get it back."
Across Bolivia, which has no outlet to the sea, the memory of a coast lost to Chile in a bloody conflict of resources in the 19th century is still alive – just like the desire to sail back into the Pacific Ocean.
These hopes are probably at the highest level in decades, as Bolivia awaits an International Court of Justice ruling on October 1 after five years of deliberations.
“Bolivia has the necessary momentum, a spirit of unity and serenity and, of course, looks forward to the outcome with a positive vision,” said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will follow the ICJ’s decision on big screens across the country, hoping that the Hague court will give a ruling in favor of Bolivia’s claim and that, after decades of firm talks, Chile is forced to negotiate a sovereign sea exit for Bolivia.
Bolivia’s charismatic president, Evo Morales, who faces a controversial fight for next year’s re-election, also has much to gain from Monday’s decision.
“We are very close to returning to the Pacific Ocean,” he promised in late August.
But some analysts believe that the court is unlikely to decide in favor of Bolivia, and that too little would change if it happened.
The United Nations body in the Netherlands does not have the power to grant Chile its territory and has stipulated that it will not determine the outcome of possible discussions.
The fact that the ICJ decision comes just six months after the final pleas were heard indicates that this case “was not complicated,” said Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert on international law.
Not only was Bolivia unsuccessful, but the last four years may have turned it back.
“The problem of access to the sea has been hijacked by the current Bolivian administration,” Zárate said.
Morales’ belligerent rhetoric weakened any residual Chilean goodwill, she suggested.
Bolivia and Chile will continue to speak at some point, but it will be extremely difficult to have discussions after that.
The two countries have not exchanged ambassadors since 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodríguez Veltzé, Bolivia’s representative in The Hague, rejected the idea that the court’s decision-making process was unusually fast.
Monday will bring Bolivia “an extraordinary opportunity to open a new era of relations with Chile” and a chance to “end the 139 years of disagreements with mutual advantages,” he said.
Calzadilla also denied that Morales – still one of Latin America’s most beloved presidents – used the maritime issue as political support.
