North Korea says there is “no chance” to unilaterally disarm as long as there is no trust
North Korea's foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that prolonging sanctions would deepen distrust in the United States and that it is impossible for his country to unilaterally give up its nuclear weapons in such circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the Global Council’s annual General Assembly that North Korea had implemented “significant steps to prove its good faith” last year, such as halting nuclear testing and missile testing, dismantling the nuclear test site and committing to non-proliferation of nuclear weapons and technology.
"However, we do not see any appropriate response from the United States," he said.
“If we cannot trust the United States, we will not trust our national security capabilities, and in such circumstances, we cannot unilaterally disarm first.”
Although Ri has resumed familiar objections from North Korea to Washington’s resistance to a “misguided” approach to denuclearization that would reward North Korea for taking steps, his statement seemed significant for not directly rejecting unilateral denuclearization, as Pyongyang has done in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at a first-ever summit between a sitting U.S. president and the leader of North Korea in Singapore on June 12, where Kim pledged to make progress toward a “denuclearization of the Korean peninsula,” while Trump offered guarantees for North Korea’s security.
North Korea sought an official end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States said Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
In addition, Washington has failed to comply with calls to ease tough international sanctions on North Korea.
"The United States insists on the 'denuclearization first' option and increases pressure through sanctions to achieve its goal in a coercive manner, and even objects to the 'war-ending declaration'," Ri said.
“The impression that sanctions can bring us to our knees is an illusion that only people who don’t know us have.
But the problem is that prolonged sanctions deepen our mistrust.”
Ri did not mention plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump that the U.S. leader referred to at the United Nations earlier this week.
In contrast, the minister highlighted the three meetings between Kim and Moon Jae-in, the president of South Korea, over the past five months, adding: "If the issue of denuclearization had been negotiated with South Korea and not with the US, denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not have reached this impasse."
Even so, the tone of Ri’s speech was very different from that of last year’s speech when he told the UN General Assembly that it was inevitable to target the US territory with missiles from North Korea after “Mr. Evil President” Trump named Kim a “missile man” on a suicide mission.
This year at the United Nations, Trump, who had threatened North Korea with “total destruction” last year, praised Kim for his courage to initiate the disarmament process, but said the work was just beginning and the sanctions would remain valid until North Korea was denuclearized.
