Harvard students take courses on how to get enough rest
A new Harvard course this year encourages students to sleep more, in an attempt to combat the growing macho culture that makes them undergo “all night” learning sessions energized with a lot of caffeine.
A scientist has discovered that often the students of the most prestigious university in the world do not even master the basic concepts of how they should take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and specialist at Brigham and Women’s Hospital, is the one who created the course, which is believed to be the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to create the course after holding a lecture on the impact of lack of sleep on the ability to learn.
“In the end, a girl came up and said, ‘Why is this being said to me just now, in the last year?’
She told me that she had never been told about the importance of sleep, which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course, first introduced this year, explains to students the essential concepts of how good sleep habits help improve academic and athletic performance as well as overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s health services, said the university decided to introduce the course after discovering that students were seriously sleep deprived during the week.
The one-hour course may involve a number of interactive tasks.
In one section, a picture of a bedroom is presented, and students can click on coffee cups, curtains, sports pants, and books to tell them what the effects of caffeine and light are and how athletic performance is affected by sleep deficiency, as well as the importance of a sleep schedule.
In another section, participants were told how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes, depression and cancer.
A campus map, with interactive icons, encourages participants to think about their daily schedule.
“We know that we can’t instantly change the behavior of students.
But we believe they have a right to know, just as anyone has a right to know the health effects of smoking,” added Professor Czeisler.
The culture that makes students proud to have learned all night still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and increasing pressure on students have turned sleep deprivation into a growing problem.
Sufficient, good-quality sleep should be a student’s “secret weapon” to combat stress, exhaustion, and anxiety, he said, and even to avoid gaining weight because sleep deprivation makes the brain think the body is hungry, which makes students feel like they are constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old California student studying chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler create the course after taking one of his first year courses at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to promote a course for all students.
The next step, he hopes, is to require all postgraduate students to complete a similar degree program before enrolling in this institution where competition is fierce.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students schedule an alarm to know when it’s time to go to bed, as well as for the waking time, and to know what are the harmful effects of the “blue light” emitted by electronic screens and LEDs, which can disrupt the circadian rhythm and cause difficulties when they try to fall asleep.
