Tim Berners-Lee, the inventor of the World Wide Web, is launching a startup that wants to compete with Facebook, Amazon and Google.
The latest project of the technology legend, Inrupt, is a company based on Solid, Berners-Lee’s open-source platform.
Solid allows users to choose where their data is stored and who has the right to access the information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee joked that the intention behind Inrupt is “global dominance.”
“Now we have to do it,” he said of the startup.
“This is a historic moment.”
The app uses Solid technology to allow people to create their own “personal online data archives” or PODs.
It can contain contact lists, programs, calendars, music libraries or other personal and professional tools.
It’s like Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify would all be available in one browser, all at once.
What is unique about this online personal data archive is that the user has complete control over who can access this type of information.
The company calls this “personal data consolidation.”
According to the company’s CEO, John Bruce, the idea is for Inrupt to contribute the right resources, processes and competencies to make Solid available to everyone.
The company currently consists of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform purchased by IBM, a team of developers working on the project, and a community of volunteer programmers.
Starting this week, technology developers around the world can create their own decentralized applications using the tools available on the Inrupt website.
Berners-Lee said he and his team aren’t talking to Facebook and Google about whether or not to introduce a complete change when their business models are completely screwed up all at once.
“We don’t ask for their permission.”
Berners-Lee wrote in a Saturday post on Medium that “the mission of Inrupt is to provide commercial energy and an ecosystem that helps protect the integrity and quality of a new Internet on Solid.”
In 1994, Berners-Lee transformed the Internet when he created the World Wide Web Consortium at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
In recent months, Berners-Lee has been an influential voice in the debate over Internet neutrality.
Even after launching Inrupt, Berners-Lee will remain the founder and director of the World Wide Web Consortium, the Web Foundation and the Open Data Institute.
“I’m incredibly optimistic for this next era of the Internet,” Berners-Lee added.
Bernard Vann: The cleric who won the Victory Cross in World War I is celebrated
The only Anglican clergyman who won a Victorian Cross medal as a fighter in World War I was celebrated in his hometown after 100 years.
Lieutenant-Colonel Bernard Vann won the medal on 29 September 1918 in the attack at Bellenglise and Lehaucourt.
He was killed by a sniper four days later and never knew he had been awarded Britain's highest military honor.
A memorial stone was unveiled Saturday by his two grandchildren during the Rushden, Northamptonshire parade.
One of his grandchildren, Michael Vann, said it was "wonderful to symbolize" that the stone would be unveiled exactly 100 years after his grandfather won the medal.
According to the London Gazette, on September 29, 1918, Lieutenant-Colonel Vann led his battalion over the Canal de Saint-Quentin "through a very thick fog and under the intense fire of artillery and machine guns".
Later, he rushed to the front line and, with “a fantastic bravery,” opened the way for the soldiers, then attacked an artillery nest on his own and managed to eliminate three of the detachment’s weapons.
Lieutenant Colonel Vann was killed by a German sniper on October 4, 1918, just a month before the end of the war.
Michael Vann, 72, said his grandfather’s actions were “something I know I’ll never be able to match, but that makes me feel humble.”
He, along with his brother, Dr. James Vann, also submitted a crown after the parade, which was conducted by the Brentwood Imperial Youth Orchestra.
Michael Vann said he "feel very honored to play a role in the parade" and added that "the value of a true hero is demonstrated by the support that a lot of people give him."
MMA fans stayed up all night to see Bellator 206, but received cartoons with Peppa Pig instead.
Imagine you’ve been up all night to watch Bellator 206, a star-studded event, just so you can’t watch the main event.
The San Jose event schedule contained 13 matches, including six on the main panel, and had to be broadcast live all night in the UK on Channel 5.
At 6 a.m., just as Gegard Mousasi was preparing to face Rory MacDonald, viewers in Britain were amazed when the broadcast was replaced by an episode of Peppa Pig.
Some were not happy at all, because they stayed up all night to watch the fight.
One fan described the move to children’s cartoons on Twitter as “a kind of bad joke.”
“Government regulations say this content isn’t suitable for 6 a.m., so they had to switch to children’s programs,” Dave Schwartz, Bellator’s senior vice president for marketing and communication, said when asked about the broadcast.
“Pig Peppa, yes.”
Scott Coker, Bellator’s president, said that in the future, they will be programming their events in such a way that they can also be watched by viewers in the UK.
“When I think about the replays, I think we could probably work it out,” Coker said.
“But it’s six in the morning on a Sunday here and we won’t be able to do that until Sunday, our hour, or Monday, their hour.
But we're working on it.
Believe me, when the program changed, I started getting a lot of text messages and they weren’t all friendly.
We tried to solve the situation, I thought it was a technical mess.
But it wasn’t that, it was government regulation.
I can promise you it won't happen again next time.
We’ll be down to five fights instead of six, as we usually do. We’ve tried to give fans more and we’ve crossed the line.
It's an unfortunate situation."
Desert Island Discs: Tom Daley 'Feeling Lower' Due to Sexuality
Olympic diver Tom Daley says he grew up knowing he was inferior to everyone else because of his sexuality, but this motivated him to succeed.
The 24-year-old said he didn’t realize until he got to school that “not everyone is like me.”
Invited to Lauren Laverne’s first Desert Island Discs show on Radio 4, he said he was talking about gay rights to give others “hope.”
He also said that when he became a parent, he cared less about the Olympics.
Kirsty Young, the regular host of the traditional show, will be missing for a few months due to an illness.
Guest on Laverne’s first edition, Daley said that as a child he felt “inferior” to others because “it wasn’t socially acceptable to like boys and girls too.”
He said: “Until now, these feelings of inferiority and the fact that I felt different were the real things that gave me the strength and stamina to achieve success.”
He wanted to prove that he was “someone,” he said, so he wouldn’t let everyone down when they finally found out about his sexuality.
The winner of two bronze medals at the Olympics has become a renowned supporter of LGBT campaigns and took advantage of this year’s Commonwealth Games appearance in Australia to ask more countries to decriminalize homosexuality.
He said he decided to speak because he felt lucky that he could live free, without consequences, and because he wanted to give others “hope”.
The three-time world champion said he was “surprised” to fall in love with a man, American filmmaker Dustin Lance Black.
Daley last year married the Oscar-winning filmmaker, who is 20 years older than him, but said the age difference was never a problem.
“When you go through so much at such a young age,” he said, “he attended the first Olympics when he was only 14, and his father died of cancer after three years, it’s hard to find someone the same age who has gone through the same good and bad times.”
In June, the pair became the parents of a boy named Robert Ray Black-Daley, which Daley says changed his “whole perspective.”
“If I had been asked last year, I would have been interested in winning a gold medal,” he said.
“You know what? There are more important things than the gold medals at the Olympics.
My Olympic gold medal is Robbie."
His son is named after his father, Robert, who died in 2011 at the age of 40 after being diagnosed with brain cancer.
Daley said his father did not accept that he was going to die and that one of the last things he wanted was to find out if they had received tickets to the 2012 London Olympics because he wanted to be in the first place.
"I couldn't say, 'You can't be first, Dad,'" he said.
“I held his hand when he stopped breathing and only after he stopped breathing and died did I finally accept that he was not invincible,” he said.
The following year, Daley competed at the 2012 Olympics and won the bronze medal.
“I knew that was what I dreamed of a lifetime, to jump in front of the spectators of my country at the Olympics, there is no better feeling,” he said.
This also inspired him in his chosen music, Proud by Heather Small, a song that encouraged him before the Olympics and still excites him.
Desert Island Discs aired on BBC Radio 4 on Sunday at 11:15 a.m.
