Germany's New Warship Delayed Again
Germany’s newest naval frigate should have been put into service in 2014 to replace the outdated Cold War warships, but this will only happen next year, due to faulty systems and rising costs, local media reported.
The commissioning of the Rheinland-Pfalz, the flagship of the new Baden-Wuerttemberg class of frigates, has now been postponed until the first half of 2019, according to Die Zeit newspaper, which cites a military spokesman.
The ship was supposed to be introduced into the maritime forces in 2014, but post-delivery issues have affected this ambitious project.
The four Baden-Wuerttemberg-class ships that the Navy commissioned in 2007 will replace the old Bremen-class frigates.
They are expected to be equipped with a powerful cannon, a range of anti-aircraft and anti-ship missiles, as well as stealth technologies, which provide a reduced radar, infrared and acoustic footprint.
Other important features will include longer maintenance periods; it should be possible for new frigates to depart on two-year missions without returning to the original port.
However, continued delays mean that these state-of-the-art warships, which are said to increase Germany’s maritime strength, will already be outdated before entering service.
The frigate F125 was discussed in the press last year when the German Navy officially refused to take over the ship and returned it to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
This was the first time the Navy returned a ship to the builder after delivery.
Not much information is available about the reasons for the refusal, but the German media cited a number of crucial “software and hardware flaws” that would have made the warship useless in a combat mission.
The software flaws were especially important because the Baden-Wuerttemberg-class ships will be operated by a crew of about 120 sailors, only half of the crews on the older Bremen-class frigates.
In addition, it turned out that the ship had too much weight, which reduced its performance and limited the Navy's ability to add future equipment.
The 7,000-ton ship Rheinland-Pfalz is believed to be twice as heavy as the German ships used in World War II.
In addition to faulty mechanisms, the price of the entire project, including crew training, has become a concern.
It is said to have reached the staggering figure of 3.1 billion euros ($3.6 billion), from the initial price of 2.2 billion euros.
The problems of the newest frigates are particularly important given the latest warnings that Germany’s maritime strength is diminishing.
Earlier this year, Hans-Peter Bartels, head of the defence commission in Germany’s parliament, acknowledged that the Navy “began to run out of vessels that could be sent to missions.”
The official said the problem has grown steadily over time as old vessels have been taken out of service without being replaced by new ones.
He lamented that none of the frigates of the Baden-Wuerttemberg class had entered service in the Navy.
The National Trust is spying on bats.
New research is being conducted on a property in the Scottish Highlands to reveal how bats use the environment to hunt their prey.
It is hoped that the findings will reveal new things about the behavior of these new flying mammals and help future conservation activities.
The study by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland will examine common dwarf bats and pygmy bats, as well as eared bats and water bats from the Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recording devices will be placed in key locations around the property to track bat activity throughout the season.
The NHS team and volunteers will also conduct mobile studies using manual detectors.
Specialized audio analysis of all recordings will estimate the frequency of sounds made by bats and which species emit certain sounds.
A habitat map and report will also be produced to create a detailed, scaled-up picture of their behaviour in the environment.
Rob Dewar, a nature conservation consultant for NTS, hopes the results will reveal which areas of habitat are most important to bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as lawn creation, and what is the best way to maintain forest meadows for bats and other associated species.
Bat populations in Scotland and across the UK have declined considerably in the last century.
They are endangered by construction and development work affecting their nests, as well as habitat loss.
Wind turbines and public lighting are risks, as are flies traps and some chemical treatments for building materials, but also attacks by domestic cats.
In fact, bats are not blind.
However, because they hunt at night, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use a sophisticated echolocation technique to accurately identify insects and obstacles on their flight path.
NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 major parks and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, is thinking very seriously about bats.
They have ten trained experts who regularly conduct surveys, monitor nests, and sometimes conduct rescue missions.
The organization has even created Scotland’s first and only bat reserve, on the Threave estate in Dumfries and Galloway, where eight out of ten species of bats are found in Scotland.
The estate manager, David Thompson, says this is ideal territory for bats.
“Here at Threave, the area is great for bats,” he says.
“We have old buildings, lots of old trees and a perfect habitat.
But there’s a lot we don’t know about bats, so the work we do here and elsewhere will help us understand why they need to grow.”
It emphasizes the importance of searching for bats before performing property maintenance work, as the mere unintended destruction of a maternal nest could kill up to 400 females and chickens, which can destroy the entire local population.
Bats are protected, and killing, harassing or disturbing them, as well as destroying their nests, are prohibited actions.
Elisabeth Ferrell, a Scottish official with the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the public to help them.
She said: "We still have a lot to learn about bats and we don't know how populations evolve for many of our species."
Ronaldo denies rape allegations as lawyers prepare to sue German magazine
