Brexit: Britain 'forever regrets' loss of automakers
Britain “would regret forever” if it lost its status as a world leader in car production after Brexit, said Business Secretary Greg Clark.
He added that it was "worrying" that Toyota UK told the BBC that if Britain leaves the EU without a deal, it would temporarily shut down production at its factory in Burnaston, near Derby.
“We need a deal,” Clark said.
The Japanese carmaker said the impact of delays at the border in the event of a no-deal Brexit could cost jobs.
The factory in Burnaston, where Toyota’s Auris and Avensis brands are manufactured, produced nearly 150,000 cars last year, 90 percent of which were exported to the rest of the European Union.
“My view is that if Britain leaves the EU at the end of March, production will stop at our factory,” said Marvin Cooke, Toyota’s chief executive at Burnaston.
Other carmakers in the UK, including Honda, BMW and Jaguar Land Rover, have said they fear leaving the EU without a deal on cross-border trade.
BMW, for example, says that after Brexit, it will close the factory in Oxford where the Mini model is produced for a month.
The main concerns are created by what manufacturers call supply chain risks in the event of a no-deal Brexit.
Toyota’s production line operates on the “fix on time” principle: for custom-made cars, parts arrive at 37-minute intervals from suppliers in the UK and the EU.
If Britain leaves the EU without a deal on March 29, there could be problems at the border, which industrial manufacturers say could cause delays and a shortage of parts.
It would be impossible for Toyota to store more of the inventory for a day at its Derbyshire factory, the company says, so production would be shut down.
Clark said May’s Chequers plan for future relations with the EU is “precisely calibrated to avoid these delays at the border.”
“We want to have the best deal, which will allow us not only to enjoy the success of the present, but also to take advantage of this opportunity,” he told BBC Radio 4’s Today.
“The evidence not only from Toyota, but also from other manufacturers, shows that we need to be able to continue to use what has been a very successful supply chain set.”
Toyota could not say how long production would have to be stopped, but warned that higher prices could reduce the factory’s long-term competitive capacity and ultimately lead to job losses.
Peter Tsouvallaris, who has been working at Burnaston for 24 years and is the head of the United union at the factory, said members are increasingly concerned: “Experience has taught me that once these jobs disappear, they don’t come back.”
A government spokesman said: “We have created a precise and credible plan for the future relationship with the EU.”
Trump's meeting with Rosenstein could be delayed again, White House says
Donald Trump’s high-level meeting with Deputy Attorney General Rod Rosenstein could be “delayed another week” as the fight for Supreme Court nominee Brett Kavanaugh continues, the White House said on Sunday.
Rosenstein is overseeing special counsel Robert Mueller, who is investigating Russia’s interference in the election, the links between Trump’s aid and Russia, and the president’s potential obstruction of justice.
Rumors of Trump firing the deputy attorney general, thus jeopardizing Mueller’s independence, have been circulating in Washington circles for months.
Earlier this month, The New York Times reported that Rosenstein discussed the possibility of wearing a microphone to record conversations with Trump and the possibility of suspending the president through Amendment 25 to the U.S. Constitution.
Rosenstein denied this report.
But last Monday he went to the White House, and reports say he was about to resign.
Instead, a meeting was announced on Thursday with Trump, who was at the time at the United Nations headquarters in New York.
Trump said he would "prefer not" to fire Rosenstein, but then the meeting was postponed to avoid a conflict with the Senate legal committee hearing, in which Kavanaugh and one of the women who accused him of sexual misconduct, Dr. Christine Blasey Ford, testified.
On Friday, Trump called for a week-long FBI investigation into the allegations against Kavanaugh, which again postponed the vote in the Senate plenary.
Trump’s press secretary Sarah Sanders appeared on Fox News on Sunday.
Asked about the meeting with Rosenstein, she said: “It has not yet been established once in this regard. It may be this week or it may be postponed by a week, taking into account all the other things that are happening now at the Supreme Court.
But we will see and always like to keep the press up to date.”
Some reporters would challenge this claim: Sanders has never had a press briefing at the White House since September 10.
Host Chris Wallace asked why.
Sanders said the reduction in the number of briefings was not caused by antipathy and TV reporters, who like to perform, though he added: "I don't deny that they like to perform."
He then suggested that direct contact between Trump and the press would be increased.
“The president attends more question-and-answer sessions than all previous presidents,” she said, adding without mentioning any evidence: “We’ve looked at the numbers.”
“There will be more briefings,” Sanders said, but “I think it’s much better for the press to have the opportunity to ask questions directly to the president of the United States, not to me.”
We try to do that most of the time and you could see that we’ve done it many times in the last few weeks and talks with the president of the United States will replace press briefings when it’s available.”
Trump usually answers questions when he leaves the White House or attends open sessions or press conferences with visiting officials.
Press conferences given exclusively by him are rare.
This week in New York, the president demonstrated why this is happening, having an impromptu appearance, in bizarre places, in front of assembled reporters.
A Secretary of State for the Ministry of Health addressed in a letter to EU employees of the National Health Service (NHS) in Scotland on fears about Brexit.
The Secretary of State wrote to EU employees working at the NHS branch in Scotland to express their gratitude on behalf of the country and their desire to remain after Brexit.
Jeane Freeman, a member of the Scottish Parliament, sent the letter as it is less than six months away from the UK’s withdrawal from the European Union.
The Scottish government has already made a commitment to bear the costs of applying for permanent resident status for EU citizens working in decentralised public services.
In his letter, Freeman wrote: “During the summer, negotiations between the UK and the EU on withdrawal continued, awaiting decision-making this autumn.
But the UK government has begun to prepare more and more for a different scenario, where there would be no deal to leave the EU.
I know this is a very stressful time for you.
For this reason, I would like to reiterate how much I appreciate the contribution of each employee, regardless of nationality.
