Foreign buyers will be charged a higher stamp court fee when buying a property in the UK
Foreign buyers will pay a higher stamp court fee when buying a property in the UK, with additional money to be used to help the homeless, according to new Conservative Party plans.
This change will neutralize the success of Corbyn’s efforts to attract young people with voting rights.
Judicial stamp fee will be applied to people who are not paying taxes in the UK
Treasury expects to raise up to 120 million pounds a year to help the homeless
Foreign buyers will be charged a higher stamp court fee when buying a property in the UK, and the additional money will be used to help the homeless, Theresa May announced today.
The move will be seen as an attempt to neutralize the success of Jeremy Corbyn’s efforts to attract young people with the right to vote, promising more affordable homes and targeting high-income people.
The higher court stamp fee will be applied to natural and legal persons who are not tax payers in the UK, and the additional money thus obtained will be used to support the government’s efforts to help the homeless.
The surcharge, which adds to the current stamp court fee, including levels raised two years ago for the second property and properties purchased for rent, could reach a value of 3%.
The Treasury expects this change to add up to 120 million pounds a year.
Approximately 13% of new-build properties in London are bought by non-residents in the UK, which leads to higher prices and makes it difficult for those who want to buy their first home.
Several prosperous areas of the country, especially in the capital, have become "ghost cities" due to the high number of foreign buyers who spend much of their time outside the country.
The new policy comes just weeks after Boris Johnson called for lowering the stamp court fee to help young people buy their first home.
He accused the large construction firms of keeping property prices high as a result of buying land without using it, and urged Theresa May to drop taxes on affordable homes in order to solve Britain’s “home problem.”
Corbyn announced a number of attractive real estate reform proposals, including rent controls and an end to unreasonable evictions.
It also wants to give councils greater powers when it comes to building new homes.
Theresa May said: “Last year I stated that I will dedicate my premiership to fulfilling the British dream of a better life for every new generation.
And that means resolving problems in the real estate market.
The UK will always be open to people who want to live, work and build a life here.
However, it is not fair that people who do not live in the UK, as well as companies based abroad, can buy homes as easily as hard-working British residents.
For too many people, the dream of owning a home has become far too distant, and living in unworthy conditions is far too real.”
Jack Ross: “My ultimate goal is to be the manager of Scotland’s national team”
Jack Ross, manager of the Sunderland football team, said his “final goal” is to become, at some point, the manager of Scotland’s national team.
The 42-year-old Scot enjoys the challenge of “revival” the northeastern club, which is currently in 3rd place in the Premier League, with a difference of three points from the first place.
He moved this summer to the Light Stadium team after winning the return of St. Mirren in the Scottish Premiership Division last season.
“I wanted to be a member of the national football team, but as a player.
We got into the B-team of the national team and that’s about it,” Ross told BBC Scotland’s Sportsound.
“But I spent a lot of my childhood watching Scotland’s Hampden matches with my father and I’ve always wanted to come back.
But I will only have this opportunity if I succeed as manager of the club.”
Ross's predecessors as Sunderland managers include Dick Advocaat, David Moyes, Sam Allardyce, Martin O'Neill, Roy Keane, Gus Poyet and Paulo Di Canio.
The former Alloa Athletic manager said he is not thrilled to be the successor to such an important club after he turned down offers from Barnsley and Ipswich Town.
“The only thing that concerns me and could affect my success is the question, ‘Can I help this team get back into the Premier League?’
There is no doubt that the structure and facilities at this club allow it to be in the Premier League,” he said.
“It’s not easy to get her there, but I think the only thing that would make me feel like a successful man is to contribute to the club’s return to the Premier League.”
Ross has only three years of driving experience, after a period as assistant manager at Dumbarton and another 15 months as a member of the Hearts training staff.
He then helped Alloa recover after relegating to Division C and managed to save St. Mirren from relegation, helping the team win the championship title next season.
Ross said he feels better now than in his entire playing career at Clyde, Hartlepool, Falkirk, St. Mirren and Hamilton Academical.
“It was a decisive moment,” he said of taking over Alloa.
“I thought it was better for me to be a manager than a player.
It may sound strange, because we had a good time, we won well and we had a few wrong moments.
But it's hard to be a player.
You have to do a lot of things and repeat them weekly.
I face similar situations as a manager when it comes to stress and pressure, but I feel it’s the right role for me.
I’ve always wanted to be a manager and now that I can do that, I feel like it’s the best thing I’ve done in my entire adult life.”
You can listen to the entire interview on Sunday, September 30, between 12:00 and 13:00 on the Radio Scotland Sportsound show.
