Earthquakes and tsunamis in Indonesia
At least 384 people have died from a powerful earthquake and tsunami that hit Indonesia’s Palu city on Friday, officials said, and the death toll is expected to rise.
Due to the disruption of communications networks, disaster authorities were unable to obtain any information from the Donggala regency, an area in northern Palu, which is closer to the epicentre of the earthquake with a magnitude of 7.5 on the Richter scale.
In Palu, more than 16,000 people were evacuated after the disaster.
Here are some key information about Palu and Donggala, on the island of Sulawesi:
Palu is the capital of the central province of Sulawesi, which sits at the end of a narrow gulf on the western coast of Sulawesi, with a population of about 379,800 in 2017.
The city was celebrating 40 years of existence when it was hit by the tsunami and the earthquake.
Donggala is a regency that stretches along a coastline with an area of more than 300 km in the northwest of Sulawesi Island.
The Regency, an administrative region that lies at the bottom of a province, has a population of about 299,200 inhabitants in 2017.
Fisheries and agriculture are central to the economy of the central province of Sulawesi, especially the Donggala coastal region.
Nickel mining activities are also important in the province, but are mostly concentrated in Morowali on the opposite coast of Sulawesi.
Palu and Donggala have been hit by tsunamis several times in the past 100 years, according to Indonesia’s Disaster Management Agency.
In 1938, a tsunami killed more than 200 people and destroyed hundreds of homes in Donggala.
In 1996, a tsunami struck the western part of Donggala, killing nine people.
Indonesia is located in the Pacific Circle of Fire, an area of intense seismic activity.
Here are some of the earthquakes and tsunamis that have occurred in recent years:
On December 26, 2004, a powerful earthquake on the west coast of Indonesia's Aceh province in northern Sumatra triggered a tsunami that struck 14 countries, killing 226,000 people on the Indian Ocean coast, more than half of whom were from Aceh.
2005: A series of powerful earthquakes hit the west coast of Sumatra in late March and early April.
Hundreds died on Nias Island off the coast of Sumatra.
2006 – A magnitude 6.8 earthquake hit the south of Indonesia’s most populous island, Java, triggering a tsunami that hit the southern coast, killing nearly 700 people.
2009: A magnitude 7.6 earthquake struck near Padang, the capital of West Sumatra.
More than 1,100 people were killed.
2010: A magnitude 7.5 earthquake hit one of the Mentawai Islands off the coast of Sumatra, triggering a tsunami of up to 10 meters in height that destroyed dozens of villages and killed around 300 people.
2016: A low-intensity earthquake occurred in the Pidie Jaya king of Aceh, causing damage and panic as people remembered the devastating 2004 earthquake and tsunami that resulted in a large number of deaths.
This time there was no tsunami, but more than 100 people died due to collapsed buildings.
2018: More powerful earthquakes have occurred on the tourist island of Lombok, killing more than 500 people, mostly on the northern side of the island.
The quake destroyed thousands of buildings and thousands of tourists were temporarily stuck under the rubble.
