How can the trade war between the United States and China be beneficial for Beijing?
The salvos announcing the start of the U.S.-China trade war have been deafening, and while there seems to be a long way to go, quarrels between the two countries could be beneficial for Beijing in the long run, experts say.
Donald Trump, the president of the United States, issued his first warning earlier this year by imposing taxes on key imports from China, including from solar panels, steel and aluminum.
The biggest escalation came this week with new taxes affecting $200 billion worth of goods, effectively levying taxes on half of all Chinese goods reaching the U.S. territory.
Beijing has avenged itself every time, most recently imposing a tax of between 5 and 10 percent on US products worth $60 billion.
China has warned that it will respond to every blow from the United States and it is unlikely that the world’s second-largest economy will take a step back in the near future.
For Washington to withdraw, China must agree to its demands, but giving in publicly to the United States would be far too humiliating for Xi Jinping, China’s president.
However, experts say that if Beijing plays its cards well, U.S. pressure on trade war could support China positively in the long run, reducing the interdependence of the two economies.
“The fact that a quick political decision in Washington or Beijing could lead to an economic downturn in both countries would actually be more dangerous than predicted so far,” said Abigail Grace, an associate researcher who focuses on Asia at the Center for New American Security.
Syria is ready for refugees to return, Foreign Minister says
Syria says it is ready for the voluntary return of refugees and calls for help in rebuilding the country devastated by a war that has lasted for more than seven years.
During his speech at the United Nations General Assembly, Foreign Minister Walid al-Moualem said the situation in the country is improving.
“Today, conditions on the ground are more stable and secure, thanks to the progress made in combating terrorism,” he said.
The government continues to rehabilitate areas destroyed by terrorists so that things return to normal.
The existing conditions allow the voluntary return of refugees to the country they were forced to leave because of terrorism and unilateral economic measures that targeted their daily lives.
The United Nations estimates that more than 5.5 million Syrians have fled the country since the war broke out in 2011.
Six million people who continue to live in the country need humanitarian assistance.
Al-Moualem said the Syrian regime would be happy to receive help in rebuilding the devastated country.
But he stressed that conditional assistance or assistance from countries sponsored by the insurgency would not be accepted.
