Red tide news: concentrations decreased in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report by the Florida Wildlife Protection Commission shows an overall drop in red tide concentrations for certain areas of the Gulf of Tampa.
According to the Commission, uneven flowering conditions are reported in areas in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties – suggesting lower concentrations.
This red tide inflorescence extends over an area of about 210 km from northern Pinellas County to southern Lee County.
The spots can be found about 16 km away in Hillsborough County, but in fewer places than last week.
Red tide was also observed in Pasco County.
Average concentrations found in or near Pinellas County were reported last week, as well as low to high concentrations in Hillsborough County, background to high concentrations in Manatee County, background to high concentrations in Sarasota County, and background to low concentrations in the county.
Irritations of the airways continue to be reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
No cases of respiratory irritation have been reported in northwest Florida in the past week.
